\description{
Fits a Distributed Lag Non-linear Model (DLNM) to quantify the association
between a climate exposure and a daily health outcome count. The function
accepts a \code{climasus_df} at stage \code{"climate"} / type \code{"distributed_lag"}
produced by \code{sus_climate_aggregate(temporal_strategy = "distributed_lag")},
constructs the bidimensional \code{crossbasis}, fits a GLM, and returns a
\code{climasus_dlnm} object with the fitted model, pre-computed \code{crosspred},
exposure-response and lag-response tables, and diagnostic statistics.
}
\section{Statistical framework}{


The DLNM models the log-linear association between an exposure history
\eqn{X_{t-0}, X_{t-1}, \ldots, X_{t-L}} and the daily count outcome
\eqn{Y_t \sim \text{Quasi-Poisson}(\mu_t)}:

\deqn{\log(\mu_t) = \alpha + \mathbf{w}_t^\top \boldsymbol{\theta}
  + \sum_{k=1}^{K} \gamma_k s_k(t)}

where \eqn{\mathbf{w}_t} is the cross-basis vector (outer product of the
exposure and lag basis matrices), and \eqn{s_k(t)} are natural splines
controlling seasonal confounding. The \strong{cumulative overall effect} across
all lags at exposure level \eqn{x} is:

\deqn{RR_{\text{cum}}(x) = \exp\!\left\{\sum_{l=0}^{L}
  [f(x,l) - f(x_0, l)]\right\}}

where \eqn{x_0} is the reference value (default: sample median).
}

\section{Family selection}{

\itemize{
\item \strong{\code{"quasipoisson"}} (default, recommended): Robust to overdispersion
(\eqn{\hat\phi > 1}). SE inflated by \eqn{\sqrt{\hat\phi}}.
Recommended when \code{disp_ratio > 1.5} (Armstrong, 2006).
\item \strong{\code{"poisson"}}: Valid only when \eqn{\hat\phi \approx 1}. Provides
AIC/BIC but underestimates SE under overdispersion.
\item \strong{\code{"negbin"}}: Redirects to \code{"quasipoisson"} with a warning —
negative binomial is incompatible with \code{dlnm::crossbasis()}.
}
}

\section{Basis selection (\code{argvar}, \code{arglag})}{
\tabular{ll}{
   \code{argvar} \tab When to use \cr
   \code{list(fun = "ns", df = 3)} \tab Mild non-linearity; conservative \cr
   \code{list(fun = "ns", df = 4)} \tab U/J shape (heat+cold, default) \cr
   \code{list(fun = "ns", df = 5)} \tab Complex dose-response; large N \cr
   \code{list(fun = "lin")} \tab Linear hypothesis test \cr
}
\tabular{ll}{
   \code{arglag} \tab When to use \cr
   \code{list(fun = "ns", df = 3)} \tab Smooth decay; temperature mortality \cr
   \code{list(fun = "ns", df = 4)} \tab Bimodal lag; cold effect \cr
   \code{list(fun = "poly", df = 2)} \tab Conservative; small samples \cr
}
}

\section{Temporal confounding (\code{ns_df}, \code{dof_per_year})}{


A natural spline \eqn{\text{ns}(\text{date}, df)} controls long-term
trends and seasonality that confound the climate-health association
(Bhaskaran et al., 2013). When \code{ns_df = NULL} the function auto-computes
\eqn{df = \texttt{dof\_per\_year} \times n_{\text{years}}}. Recommended:
\itemize{
\item \code{dof_per_year = 4}: 1-2 year series; captures annual seasonality.
\item \code{dof_per_year = 6}: Subtropical Brazil; stronger seasonality.
\item \code{dof_per_year = 8}: Arboviral diseases; sub-seasonal variation.
\item \code{ns_df = NULL} with \code{dof_per_year = 0}: suppress time control
(use only when exposure is already an anomaly from climatology).
}
}

